---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Affiliate disclosure — DeviceLab"
  description="Which of our outbound links are affiliate links, who pays us for what, and why it doesn't affect the ranking."
>
  <section class="dl-page-header">
    <div class="dl-eyebrow-hero">DEVICELAB / DISCLOSURE</div>
    <h1>Affiliate disclosure</h1>
    <p class="dl-blurb">
      Which outbound links are affiliate links, who pays us for what,
      and why it doesn't affect the ranking. Last updated: July 2026.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="dl-container" style="padding: 12px 16px 40px; max-width: 68ch;">
    <h2>Short version</h2>
    <p>
      Some of the outbound links on device pages are affiliate links.
      If you click one and buy something, we may earn a commission —
      at no additional cost to you. That's how we fund the site.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Nothing about the ranking depends on any affiliate
      relationship.</strong> Devices we don't earn a penny on can and
      do outrank devices we do earn on. The scoring engine has no
      access to price, offer, or commission data — enforced in code.
    </p>

    <h2>Who pays us for what</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Amazon Associates (UK &amp; US).</strong> We're
        participants in the Amazon EU Associates Programme
        (<span class="mono">gtaviai-21</span>) and the Amazon Services LLC
        Associates Program (<span class="mono">gtaviai-20</span>). Amazon buy
        buttons carry those tags. We earn a percentage of qualifying
        sales made after clicking through.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Awin (publisher ID 2972385).</strong> Some
        manufacturer buttons — Lenovo, Dell, HP, ASUS, MSI, Razer, LG,
        Samsung, Microsoft, Huawei, Acer, Framework — are wrapped with
        Awin's affiliate redirector as merchants approve us into their
        programmes. We earn a per-merchant commission on qualifying
        sales.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Everything else</strong> — search-URL fallbacks,
        manufacturer links for brands we're not yet approved for,
        pair-with cross-sell links — is <em>not</em> affiliate-tagged.
        No commission, no tracking, standard outbound link.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why the ranking is safe from this</h2>
    <p>
      The DeviceLab codebase separates scoring from monetisation by
      design:
    </p>
    <ul class="mono" style="font-size: 13px;">
      <li>src/lib/scoring.ts — pure function of axis scores × weights. Zero imports from merchants.</li>
      <li>src/data/merchants.ts — the affiliate wrapping code. Zero imports from scoring.</li>
      <li>src/lib/awin.ts — the Awin URL wrapper. Zero imports from anything upstream of the merchant layer.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      If a merchant tries to pay for a higher rank, changing that
      ranking would require altering the scoring module and passing
      code review. The answer will be no.
    </p>

    <h2>What we don't do</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Sponsored placements or "featured" positions in the ranking.</li>
      <li>Paid inclusion in the catalogue.</li>
      <li>Editorial partnerships that touch the score.</li>
      <li>Retargeting, remarketing, or ad-tech tracking pixels on any page.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How to spot affiliate links</h2>
    <p>
      Every outbound retail button explicitly says which merchant it
      goes to ("Amazon UK →", "Lenovo store →"). All outbound retail
      links carry <span class="mono">rel="sponsored noopener"</span> so
      your browser and search engines can distinguish them from
      editorial links.
    </p>

    <h2>Questions</h2>
    <p>
      For anything that doesn't fit above — including
      "how much have you earned from device X" — email us via the
      <a href="/contact/">contact page</a>. We're happy to answer.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
